Write the Introduction and Methodology sections of an experiment investigating the effect of air pollution on the thickness of the shell of eggs from great crested grebes (Podiceps cristatus cristatus) nesting on Ilwol Lake and Andong Lake.

Introduction

Two related reports are provided below. (Click to download.) You don't have time to read these, so the abstracts are provided here, too. Now scroll down to see the explanation for the methodology.

Cortinovis, Galassi, Melone, Saino, Porte, & Bettinetti (2008) - Organochlorine contamination in the Great Crested Grebe (Podiceps cristatus) - Effects on eggshell thickness and egg steroid levels.pdf

Abstract

Eggs of the Great Crested Grebe (Podiceps cristatus) were collected from a breeding area on Lake Maggiore (Northern Italy) from 2001 to 2005 in the vicinity of a p,p′-DDT manufacturer, whose production was stopped in 1996. DDT homologue and PCB congener levels were determined and compared to levels in eggs collected from other breeding areas on Lake Maggiore and in a presumably less contaminated area on Lake Garda. Although Lake Garda eggs on average possessed a lower level of p,p′-DDE than Lake Maggiore eggs, they had significantly higher levels of PCBs and could not be used as a reference population for the measurement of eggshell thickness. Nevertheless, a negative linear relationship was found between p,p′-DDE concentration and eggshell thickness for eggs collected from both lakes, indicating a possible causal relationship. Testosterone and 17ẞ-estradiol concentrations were also determined for eggs collected from both lakes in 2004. Average concentrations of both hormones were the lowest in eggs from Lake Maggiore; however, the very high variability within broods did not result in any significant difference between the lakes.

Ding, Yang, Yang, Ai, Bai, & Zhang (2019) - Variations in tree sparrow (Passer montanus) egg characteristics under environmental metal pollution.pdf

Abstract

Environmental metal pollution is known to adversely affect bird reproduction, for which the variations of egg characteristics are considered very important. Our study explored whether variations in egg characteristics, such as egg volume, eggshell spotting pattern, eggshell coloration, and eggshell thickness, were correlated with heavy metal levels (Cu, Zn, Pb, and Cd) and Ca levels in the eggshells of tree sparrows (Passer montanus), a widespread passerine species. Eggs were collected from a long-term heavy metal polluted area (Baiyin, BY, northwest China) and a relatively unpolluted area (Liujiaxia, LJX, northwest China). Our results showed that the embryonated (eggshell: Cu: p = 0.003, Pb: p = 0.002) and non-embryonated (egg contents: Pb: p = 0.044, Ca: p = 0.045) eggs collected from BY contained relatively higher metal concentrations than those from LJX. Eggs from BY were smaller in volume (p < 0.01) and thinner in eggshell thickness (p < 0.01) than those from LJX. Mean egg volume increased with clutch size in BY (p = 0.017), which was also accompanied by an increase in the within-clutch coefficient of variation (CV) for egg volume (p = 0.045). Clutches with a higher CV for egg volume tended to contain higher concentrations of Zn and Pb (Zn: p = 0.084; Pb: p = 0.081) in the eggshells from BY. No differences were found in the eggshell spotting coverage ratio of eggs; however, eggshells were much darker in BY than in LJX. A more aggregated eggshell spotting distribution indicated higher eggshell Zn and Pb levels (BY: Zn: p = 0.040, Pb: p = 0.076; LJX: Pb: p = 0.066). The results demonstrate that the egg characteristics of tree sparrows can be used as indicators ofmetal pollution, especially for thewithin-clutch CV for egg volume, eggshell spotting pattern and eggshell coloration.

This experiment investigated the interaction between temperature and chemicals on the growth of roses (Rosa hybrida). It was conducted over 57 days: four weeks before 21st March, and four afterwards. Explanation of the Introduction, Methodology, and Results

DO NOT COPY ANY PHRASES FROM THIS EXPLANATION.

This experiment investigated whether five mosquito species respond differently to repellents. Repellents are chemicals that mosquitoes do not like, so they stay away from people who use them; they do not kill mosquitoes. The five species were Aedes aegypti, Anopheles sinensis, Culex pipiens pallens, Culex pipiens molestus, and Ochlerotatus togoi. Three types of repellent were studied: lemongrass oil, vanillin, and xanthoxylum oil. Volunteers (N [total number] = 80, Mdn [median] age = 25, s.d. [standard deviation] = 2.3) were divided into 20 groups of four. All wore a t-shirt and shorts. Five groups' exposed skin was sprayed with lemongrass oil, five groups were sprayed with vanillin, and five groups were sprayed with xanthoxylum oil. The remaining groups (controls) were not sprayed. Participants' skin was examined for pre-existing mosquito bites, which were counted. Five chambers were prepared, each containing ten female mosquitoes—one chamber for each species. One group with each repellent and a control group (total 20 participants) entered each chamber. walking slowly and randomly around the chamber for 30 minutes. After leaving the chambers, participants' exposed skin was re-examined, and mosquito bites were counted. on average, all repellents performed better than the control (no repellent), though participants sprayed with vanillin were bitten more by Ochlerotatus togoi than control participants were. Overall, xanthoxylum oil performed best for all mosquito species, but not for all species considered separately. The greatest effect on a particular species was by lemongrass oil on Culex pipiens molestus. ANOVAs (statistical tests) showed that the number of bites did not differ significantly by species [F(4, 75) = 2.19, p < 0.08], but they differ significantly by repellent [F(3, 76) = 18.79, p < 0.00001]. Related studies

You will need to reference related work to compare findings. You can use the studies provided below, and you can use other sources, too.

DO NOT COPY ANY PHRASES FROM THIS EXPLANATION.

Kim, Kim, Jung, Ilyasov, Jang, & Lee (2019) - Spatial releasing properties and mosquito repellency of cellulose-based beads containing essential oils and vanillin-1.pdf

Simplified abstract

Researchers investigated the effectiveness of using wood pulp-based porous cellulose beads, called Viscopearl, as a mosquito repellent by applying lemongrass oil, xanthoxylum oil, and vanillin to them. Dispersed through an air conditioner, these beads provided a continuous and controlled release of the active ingredients, and their quality was verified using gas chromatography–mass spectrometry analysis. The study found that the Viscopearl-equipped air conditioner repelled mosquitoes well without affecting the air conditioner's plastic components, making it a potential indoor mosquito repellent agent.

Lee & Lee (2004) - Laboratory assessment of a formulated Bacillus thuringiensis var. israelensis against five medically important species of mosquito larvae in Republic of Korea-1.pdf

Simplified abstract

Bacillus thuringiensis var. israelensis de Barjac (Bti) was tested in a laboratory to kill five types of mosquito larvae: Aedes aegypti, Anopheles sinensis, Culex pipiens pallens, Culex pipiens molestus, and Ochlerotatus togoi. The results showed that Bactosec®, an industrial formulation of Bti, was effective against all five species. Aedes aegypti was the most susceptible, with the lowest concentration of Bti needed for mortality. Culex pipiens pallens was the least susceptible, needing a four times higher concentration for 90% mortality. The study suggests that Bactosec® has great potential for controlling medically important mosquitoes.

assignments.assignment_description:
An interesting adverb that often confuses learners is the word yesterday. According to Swan [1, p. 19], words such as yesterday, today, and tomorrow are adverbs of time and definite frequency, along with phrases such as in June, weekly, and every year. He explains their usage as follows.

I’m going to London today.
What did you do afterwards?
She has a new hairstyle every week.

Front position is also common if the adverb is not the main focus of the message.

Today I’m going to London.
Every week she has a new hairstyle.

Reference

[1]         M. Swan, Practical English usage, 3rd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2005.
